did.abstract: Collection contains memos, reports, correspondence, and subject files and is arranged in series according to the origin or type of documentation.

accessrestrict.head: Use of Materials:
accessrestrict.p: Access to the collection is unrestricted.

userestrict.head: Copyright:
userestrict.p: The Charles Babbage Institute holds the copyright to all materials in the collection, except for items covered by a prior copyright (such as published materials). Researchers may quote from the collection under the fair use provisions of the copyright law (Title 17, U.S. Code).

acqinfo.head: Acquisition:
acqinfo.p: The records were given to the Charles Babbage Institute by Unisys Corporation in 1991, accession 991-35.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation:
prefercite.p: Burroughs Corporation Records, ElectroData Division Records (CBI 90), Charles Babbage Institute, University of Minnesota, Minneapolis.

arrangement.head: Arrangement of Collection
arrangement.p: The materials in this collection are arranged into the following groups:

list.item: Medium Systems Manufacturing and Engineering Records
Logic Schematics for B205 and B5000
Fred Kalbach and Norm Kreuder Papers

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The ElectroData Corporation was taken over by Burroughs in June of 1956. ElectroData, originally a division of the Consolidated Electrodynamics Corporation, was spun off and then went public. This acquisition gave Burroughs a good start in the computer industry as ElectroData had built the Datatron 205 and was working on the Datatron 220.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The collection contains memos, reports, correspondence, and subject files and is arranged in series according to the origin or type of documentation.

note.p: This is one series of the Burroughs Corporation Records (CBI 90). Please see the other series finding aids for further information regarding the Burroughs Corporation.

controlaccess.p: This collection is indexed under the following headings in the catalog of the University of Minnesota Libraries. Researchers desiring materials about related topics, persons or places should search the catalog using these headings.
